<div class="ru-top-story">
<h6 class="kicker"></h6>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">TPG Capital, the 22-year-old private equity firm, suffered more than other firms when the financial crisis took hold in 2008. But now, as it contemplates a future initial public offering, TPG is coming back â this time with smaller deals and a recalibrated approach to private equity, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/03/24/hurt-in-crisis-tpg-pursues-smaller-deals">William Alden and Michael J. de la Merced write in DealBook</a></b>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>TPGâs new approach is in large part a response</b> to a number of gigantic deals it made in the pre-crisis era that ultimately soured, resulting in disappointing returns and disgruntled investors. Now, TPG is looking more at <b>buying minority stakes</b> in often fledgling companies, portraying itself to potential investors as a wiser firm than it was during the reckless days before the crisis. Indeed, TPGâs most prominent deal activity of late lies far outside the realm of traditional leveraged buyouts. Instead, its growth capital arm, TPG Growth, is <b>investing in fast-growing start-ups</b> like the car service Uber and the home-sharing company Airbnb.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">BOX TO GO PUBLIC <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> Box, an online storage service that aims to become an essential part of cloud computing-based business, revealed plans on Monday to raise up to $250 million in an initial public offering, <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/03/25/technology/box-a-cloud-storage-firm-plans-ipo.html">Quentin Hardy writes in The New York Times</a></b>. Boxâs move vaulted it ahead of other cloud businesses, including its rival Dropbox, which are also expected to announce plans to go public this year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>In a recent round of private funding</b>, Box, which is not yet profitable, was valued at $2 billion, but would most likely be worth several times that after the I.P.O. The company, which was founded in 2005, reported revenue of $124.2 million in the fiscal year ended Jan. 31, and had losses of $168.6 million. A year earlier, the company had revenue of $58.8 million, and losses of $112.6 million. In many ways, Boxâs ability to attract investors hinges on the idea that <b>spending to attract customers at the beginning will generate future subscription fees</b>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b><a href="//on.wsj.com/1oW4C5H">The Wall Street Journal writes</a></b>: âOf the 225,000 organizations who use Box, about 15 percent pay for the service. And <b>among the 25 million registered users, only 7 percent are paying</b>. That means Box has the chance to sell its extra features, such as better security, to millions of individuals at tens of thousands companies who already use the site.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> QUESTIONING COKEâS COMPENSATION PLAN <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> When Coca-Cola sent out its annual report and proxy statement to shareholders earlier this month, one analyst took issue with what he calculated to be as much as $24 billion allocated toward stock-based rewards for the companyâs senior people, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/03/24/a-question-of-whats-a-reasonable-reward">Andrew Ross Sorkin writes in the DealBook column</a></b>. The analyst, David Winters, was, in fact, so stunned by the figure that he sent a letter last Friday to Coca-Cola shareholders and its board, saying he found <b>âno reasonable basisâ for such an excessive compensation plan</b>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Mr. Winters sent a separate letter to Warren E. Buffett</b>, who controls 9.1 percent of Cokeâs stock through Berkshire Hathawayâs holdings. The compensation plan requires shareholder approval, so Mr. Buffett, as one of the companyâs biggest and most influential investors, holds considerable sway over the plan. By his account, Mr. Winters is upset by the proposed compensation program because âwe want to own Coca-Cola foreverâ and the plan âhurts the underlying investment case.â For its part, <b>Coca-Cola says Mr. Wintersâs analysis âis misinformed and does not reflect the facts,â</b> arguing that the plan extends to a large group of employees and is <b>not limited to senior executives</b>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>What bothers Mr. Winters most</b> is that the compensation plan would dilute shareholders, whom he said had expected Coca-Colaâs share buyback program to make each share worth more, not less. In a letter to the board, he wrote, âInstead of meaningfully reducing shares outstanding and growing value on a per-share basis, this share repurchase program will merely help to <b>offset the new shares issued to management under the plan.</b>â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> Januaryâs <b>Federal Housing Finance Agency house price index</b> is out at 9 a.m. Januaryâs <b>Standard &#038; Poorâs/Case-Shiller home price index</b> is released at 9 a.m. <b>New home sales</b> for February are out at 10 a.m. The <b>consumer confidence index</b> for March is out at 10 a.m.<b> Y Combinatorâs Demo Day</b> begins at 10 a.m. at the Computer History Museum in Mountain View, Calif. <b>Dennis P. Lockhart</b>, president of the Atlanta Fed, discusses the economic outlook at 4 p.m. <b>Charles I. Plosser</b>, president of the Philadelphia Fed, speaks at 7 p.m. in New York. The <b>House Financial Services Committee</b> holds a hearing entitled âWhy Debt Mattersâ at 10 a.m.</p>
