<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">5 FORMER MADOFF AIDES FOUND GUILTY OF FRAUD <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> In a win for Preet Bharara, the United States attorney in Manhattan, a federal jury on Monday found five associates of the convicted swindler Bernard L. Madoff guilty on 31 counts of aiding one of the largest Ponzi schemes in history, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/03/24/5-former-madoff-employees-found-guilty-of-fraud">Rachel Abrams and Diana B. Henriques write in DealBook</a></b>. The trial, which lasted more than five months, focused on whether the employees had knowingly committed securities fraud and other deceptive acts to mislead auditors and investors in Bernard L. Madoff Investment Securities, the firm Mr. Madoff founded in the early 1960s.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Federal prosecutors made the case that the <b>defendants were well aware of the fraud taking place</b> at Mr. Madoffâs firm, contending three former employees had conspired in various ways to lie to customers, cheat on taxes and falsify records at Madoff Securities. The government also accused two computer programmers of helping sustain the $17 billion Ponzi scheme by knowingly creating computer programs that could create fake trades and records. <b>The five aides each face decades in prison</b>, although the judge will be able to use her discretion in sentencing. Mr. Madoff is currently serving 150 years in prison.</p>
</div>
